        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3038410340" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3454692728197316748">There’s something so very soothing about these memoirs. Whether James Herriot’s appointments were with a difficult bull needing a nose ring or a favourite dog who’d injected rat poison, or cat hit by a car, there is a general sense of practicality, competence and compassion that permeates each interaction between James and his clients and patients. <br/>I wonder how much a large animal vet’s life differs now (obviously meds and surgical procedures are better now). I imagine the long days and night vi</span>
  <span id="freeText3454692728197316748" style="display:none">There’s something so very soothing about these memoirs. Whether James Herriot’s appointments were with a difficult bull needing a nose ring or a favourite dog who’d injected rat poison, or cat hit by a car, there is a general sense of practicality, competence and compassion that permeates each interaction between James and his clients and patients. <br />I wonder how much a large animal vet’s life differs now (obviously meds and surgical procedures are better now). I imagine the long days and night visits would be familiar to today’s doctors. What I do know is I find these reminiscences by Herriot quite enjoyable.</span>
